title: For Sale:  Excellent condition HK SL8-1
location: Raleigh/Cary/Apex, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
I bought this unfired back in the spring . I had about 200 rounds on it and it developed a crack in the chamber face . HK replaced it with a NEW factory barrel ,documentation is available . I got it back and slow fired about 40 rounds through , basically taking a shot and then pushing a brush and then a patch . I always out through the chamber , and it was a chore to say the least , but whatever , that's what I do with a new barrel . The main reason I do this is to reduce fouling . I've been busy shooting other stuff and never went back to it . If you shoot 62gr or higher ammo this thing is a true tack driver . The way the barrel is crowned it also sounds like a cannon , so I have been told . You will not shoot a smoother more accurate rifle for the money . It's got a 20" Chrome lined hammer forged barrel . This is the same action as on the G-36 rifle . 

The only reason I'm selling it is to move on to a bolt rifle .  I think with 69 or even 77gr ammo with this SL8 you could have some fun out to 6 or 700 yards . I know most folks buy these to do the conversion and I do understand that , but this rifle is a serious shooter the way it is . Anyway , here's what I got in addition to the rifle ;

1-The manual .
2-9ea. factory 10 round magazines .
3-The top rail you see in the picture and the one that came with it stock .
4-A piccatinny rail on the bottom of the handguard . 
5-A couple of spacer rings ( 2 ) for the buttstock .

title: For Sale:  Unissued / Unfired CZ-52
location: Apex, NC, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Yes, you read that right.  I have a completely unissued, unfired CZ-52 (more accurately known as a vz. 52) pistol for sale.  How, you ask?  The good folks at CzechPoint stumbled across them a few years ago, and I will let them tell the story: 

-----

How are these unissued vz. 52 pistols made available?  While opening boxes of ‘very good condition’ pistols that were sold previously, CzechPoint discovered a very limited quantity of unissued pistols.  We put these pistols to the side and are now selling these last few remaining ones.   It is ‘first come, first served on these unissued pistols.

Pistols are unissued, but some have more handling and storage marks than others (after all, these pistols are 60 years old!).  Further, some pistols will exhibit patina on the slide and/or frame and possible dings in metal or grips from handling by Czech armorers.  These pistols were stored in wooden vz.52 pistol boxes and you can see this wooden storage box in one of the thumbnails. Pistols were wrapped in plastic, and every five to ten years, were removed from the wooden boxes and plastic bags and completely inspected/function-checked by Czech armorers. Holsters are in very good serviceable condition.  Just to confirm, vz. 52 pistol holster leather varies so the holster you receiver may not match the photo (there are light and dark color holsters in addition to different types of texture).  Further, lanyards differ in material so not all lanyards will look like the one in the photo.

The magazine included with the pistol had been inserted and removed a number of times, so the finish on the magazine will be worn.  In addition, the magazine included with the pistol had been used to remove the barrel from the slide during inspection by Czech armorers.  Therefore, you’ll see cosmetic wear on magazine floor plates.  The pistol shown the in the photo is a good representation of our current unissued inventory.

The ‘CzechPoint’ import engraving is on the frame and can only be seen when the pistol is turned upside down.  A 19 page color instruction manual is included – written by CzechPoint.  We may be a little partial, but we feel it is the best manual written on the vz.52.

-----

I snagged two when they were available, shot one, and held on to the other until I wanted the investment for something else, and here we are. 

The gun comes with its original plastic shrink wrap (complete with the cosmoline I have not cleaned off), a magazine, a holster, a lanyard, a cleaning rod, and the aforementioned instruction manual.  And, yeah, it has not been fired, as far as I can tell.  I will the pictures tell the story.

Asking $450 or best offer for the whole kit.  A little steep, I know, but it is something of a collector’s item, what with it being unfired, and it is doubtful any more in this condition will hit the market any time soon.  Feel free to ping me if you have any questions.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Nightvision rifle scope, Yukon 2.5 NVRS Titanium
location: Keene area/SWNH, New Hampshire, United States
postcontent:
$450 or best offer, bitcoin, or trades.

I'm treating myself to higher-end nightvision and will no longer need this scope.  It is in excellent condition (I've babied it).  I am the original owner and purchased it at Gander Mountain for $540, and it paid for itself in coyote and fox pelts the first year I owned it.  

The scope has been mounted mostly upon my AR15 coyote rig, and has spent slightly less time on my Remington 597.  On full moon nights, shots out to 175 yards are a no-brainer.  On pitch-black cloudy nights (without an auxiliary IR torch), kill shots out to about 100 yards are possible.  If you have a good auxiliary variable/adjustable beam IR torch, you can stretch that kill zone back out to 175-200.  I DO have a TNVC ELR Torch-V that I would be willing to include for more cash or a better trade.

If you've never owned any NV gear but have been curious, this would be an excellent entry point for you at a reasonable price.  You will spend loads of time in the back yard looking through it, just for fun.  Hunting with it is a blast.

The tube on this scope is flawless; as in - more flawless than some brand new Gen2/Gen3 military-grade tubes I've seen.  If you know about NV tubes, you know they're difficult to manufacture, so even flawed tubes make it into top-priced scopes, even for military purposes.  This scope has zero spots.  None at all.  Super clear.  It also has excellent glass.  Scope has never been pointed toward a light source.  It is as perfect in form and function as it was the day I bought it.

It runs on 2 AA batteries.  I have always removed the batteries from the scope when the season ended.  2AA batteries will last this scope an entire hunting season; it is extremely energy efficient.

The scope also has an input for recording your hunts (recording unit not included, but available online, ebay, etc).

I am usually free on Monday nights if you would like to come look through the scope.  Serious inquiries only, no tire kickers.

title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 1866
postcontent: The Model 1866 was the first rifle manufactured under the Winchester banner. An improvement on the 1860 Henry rifle, the Model 1866 still fired the Henry rim fire round and retained most of the Henry design. This 2nd Model has a less severe drop at the rear of the receiver and flares at the forward edge to better mate with the forend. The stocks have been refinished and repaired and the barrel has been refinished, but likely long ago. The rifle has seen some rough use. The left side of the muzzle is compressed from a strong force. We can only imagine how that happened. Visions of confrontations with road agents or other hostiles comes to mind, with a previous owner bravely fending off danger before a lucky shot put him down, hurling this rifle into the rocks below. In any case, from the use this Winchester exhibits, it’s possible that it made it through more than one scrape. The Model 1866 was the beginning of the Winchester legend and was in production for 32 years, long after improvements in design, ammunition and technology provide more modern and powerful rifles. The longevity if the 1866 is a testament to quality of design and execution. What a thrill it would be to own an original example of the first classic Winchester.
